<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How do I calculate greenhouse heater size?", answer: "The formula is BTU/hr = Surface Area × Temperature Difference × U-Value. Surface area is the total exterior area in square feet (2 × (LW + LH + WH) for a rectangular box). Temperature difference is the desired inside temperature minus the lowest expected outside temperature. U-value is the heat transfer coefficient of the glazing material — 1.15 for single poly, 0.65 for double glass or twin-wall polycarbonate. A 10 × 20 × 8 ft hoop house covered in single poly needs roughly 29,900 BTU/hr to keep it at 50°F when it is 10°F outside." },
  { question: "What U-value should I use for my greenhouse?", answer: "Single layer polyethylene: 1.15. Double inflated poly: 0.70. Single glass: 1.13. Double insulated glass: 0.65. Twin-wall polycarbonate: 0.65. Triple-wall polycarbonate: 0.58. Fiberglass: 1.00. Lower U-value means better insulation and a smaller (cheaper, quieter, easier) heater. Upgrading from single to double layer poly cuts heat loss roughly in half and is the single best upgrade for a heating greenhouse." },
  { question: "Is BTU or watts better for sizing?", answer: "They are the same thing measured differently. 1 watt = 3.412 BTU/hr. Gas heaters are almost always rated in BTU/hr; electric heaters in watts. A 5,000 watt electric heater delivers 17,060 BTU/hr. The calculator shows both so you can shop whichever type is easier for your situation. Gas is usually cheaper per BTU for larger greenhouses; electric is cleaner and simpler for small hobby greenhouses under 200 square feet." },
  { question: "Should I oversize the heater?", answer: "Moderately yes. Add 10 to 20 percent to the calculated BTU requirement for margin. Wind increases heat loss significantly — a 15 mph wind can double effective heat loss. Also, consider your backup plan for rare extreme cold events. Oversizing too much wastes money and causes the heater to short-cycle, which shortens its life. 20 percent margin plus an emergency plan for the rare 20-degree-below-forecast night is the practical sweet spot." },
  { question: "How much does it cost to heat a greenhouse?", answer: "Heating cost depends on fuel price, outside temperature, greenhouse size, and glazing. As a rough rule, a 10 × 20 ft single-poly hoop house kept at 50°F in a USDA zone 6 winter costs 200 to 500 dollars in propane or 300 to 700 dollars in electricity per month. Upgrading to double-layer poly cuts the bill in half. Heating only to 35-40°F (frost protection) instead of 50°F cuts it further. Many growers use only passive solar plus thermal mass plus emergency heat, which can work down to 30°F outside." }
]) %>

